Description of the data:

Variables:

  • ID - identification number of the dower
  • rok - year of the record
  • idd - identification number of the dynasty
  • pos - status of the recipient (NA - unknown, 0 - high nobility, 1 - pauperized high nobility, 2 - lower nobility)
  • idd.1
  • pau - status of the donor (0 - high nobility, 1 - pauperized high nobility)
  • sum - the value of the dower
  • vec - widower (1)/non-widower(0)
  • va - widow (1)/non-widow(0)
  • addtrans - no changes to the dower (0) / adding to the dower (1) / transfer of the dower to different assets (2)

Ratio between dower and dowry

library(ggplot2)

# complete observations only
dowry <- c(200, 1000, 250, 200, 350, 600, 100, 200, 200)
dower <- c(260, 1000, 250, 500, 500, 1000, 150, 200, 500)
coefs <- dower/dowry

#mean(coefs)
summary(coefs)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   1.000   1.000   1.429   1.544   1.667   2.500
df <- data.frame(dowry = dowry, dower = dower, coefs = coefs)

ggplot(data = df, aes(x = coefs)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins = 10, 
                 color = "black", 
                 fill = "white") + 
  xlab("Ratio between dower and dowry") + 
  ylab("Number of observations") + 
  ggtitle("Figure 1: Ratio between dower and dowry")

According to Vsehrd, the dower should be 2.5 times higher than the dowry

That does not hold true. Although we know both the values of dower and dowry only in nine cases, the dower reached the ratio of 2.5 only in 2 of them. In the rest of the observations, it did not reach even 2 and the most common ratio was 1.

Correlations

# Correlation between dower and status of the donors
cor(vena_basic$sum[!is.na(vena_basic$sum == TRUE)], 
    vena_basic$pau[!is.na(vena_basic$sum == TRUE)], 
    method = "pearson")
## [1] -0.345052
# Correlation between dower and status of the recipient 
# (excluding the unknown dynasties)
kor2 <- vena_basic[vena_basic$pos != "?", ]
kor2$pos <- as.numeric(kor2$pos)
cor(kor2$pos[!is.na(kor2$sum == TRUE)], 
    kor2$sum[!is.na(kor2$sum == TRUE)], 
    method = "spearman")
## [1] -0.2969235

The correlation coefficient indicate that both the status of the donor and the recipient influenced the size of the dower. In particular, higher status led to higher dower.

# Who married who (absolute numbers)
table(vena_basic$pau, vena_basic$pos)
##    
##       ?   0   1   2
##   0  49 110  15  16
##   1  14  18   9  11
# Who married who (row percent)
prop.table(table(vena_basic$pau, vena_basic$pos), 1)
##    
##              ?          0          1          2
##   0 0.25789474 0.57894737 0.07894737 0.08421053
##   1 0.26923077 0.34615385 0.17307692 0.21153846

The tables show that the groom from high nobility married predominantly brides from high nobility. However, grooms from pauperized dynasties had higher chances to marry a bride from higher nobility than the other way around.

The regression model of dower

Hypotheses:

H1: Higher the status of the donor, the higher the value of the dower.

H2: Higher the status of the recipient, the higher the value of the dower.

H3: Widows received lower dowers than non-widows.

H4: Widowers gave lower dower than non-widowers because it is expected that they have children from previous marriage.

H5: Dowers to which were added later were lower than the rest (because they were given by young noblemen who had not much capital)

# Recode the status of the recipient into two categories
## 0 = high nobility
## 1 = the rest (pauperized, lower, unknown dynasties)
vena_basic$pos[vena_basic$pos != 0] <- 1

model1 <- lm(log1p(sum) ~ pau + factor(pos), data = vena_basic)
summary(model1)
